            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Lin\u2019s story began in the Sunset District, the younger of two daughters born to parents who ran a modest dry-cleaning business. Her childhood was steeped in the rhythms of work and community, her parents' dedication to their craft a quiet lesson in perseverance. While her older sister excelled academically, Mei found solace and expression in drawing, filling countless sketchbooks with observations of city life. Art, though, was seen as a hobby, not a path by her pragmatic immigrant parents.\n\nShe dutifully enrolled in City College, intending to pursue something practical, but the siren song of the art department was too strong to resist. She took painting and design classes unofficially, her heart drawn to the vibrant local art scene. Financial realities, however, dictated a different trajectory. She left college without a degree, taking a position in administrative support at a non-profit that organized cultural events. It was here she discovered a different form of creative expression \u2013 the meticulous orchestration of showcasing art.\n\nYears passed in roles that edged closer to her passion, the transition to Junior Exhibition Coordinator at a management firm a culmination of quiet ambition and acquired skills. It wasn\u2019t the grand museum she once dreamed of, but it offered a connection to the arts world and a steady income. At 48, she was comfortable, her $65,000 salary supporting her small apartment near Golden Gate Park.\n\nHer daily routine was a gentle rhythm. A sunrise bike ride along dedicated paths through the city, the cool air a bracing start to her day. Work involved managing logistics, coordinating vendors, and ensuring art installations ran smoothly. Evenings were often spent sketching in her apartment, a silent conversation with her younger self. Relationships were solid but few; a small circle of friends from the dry-cleaning days and appreciative colleagues. Romance had been fleeting, a quiet ache she\u2019d learned to live with.\n\nSan Francisco was more than a city; it was her home, her muse. The diverse neighborhoods, the ever-changing fog, the hidden staircases \u2013 all fueled her artistic soul. Her hope was simple: to find a way, even in her current role, to directly facilitate opportunities for emerging local artists, perhaps even curate a small show of her own. It was a quiet aspiration, born from a lifetime of appreciating the art of others and a lingering desire to finally put her own mark on the canvas of her city."
